expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>3937</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-00IN</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00IN.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Relational composite</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>17</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
href="marcelofiore.xml"
type="local"
addr="marcelofiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Given <fr:link
href="jms-00I7.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00I7">relations</fr:link> <fr:tex>R \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  B</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>S \colon  B \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  C</fr:tex>, we can define the <fr:em><fr:strong>relational composite</fr:strong></fr:em> <fr:tex>S \circ  R \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  C</fr:tex> in a way that generalises composition of functions. In particular, we define <fr:tex>S \circ  R</fr:tex> to be the following subset of <fr:tex>A \times  C</fr:tex>:</fr:p><fr:tex
display="block">   \begin {aligned}  S \circ  R &amp; \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  C \\    S \circ  R &amp;=    { \mathopen {} \left \{      { \mathopen {} \left ( a,c \right ) \mathclose {}} \in  A \times  C     \mid      \exists  b \in  B \mathpunct {.}     a \mathrel {R}b  \land  b \mathrel {S} c    \right \} \mathclose {}}    \end {aligned} </fr:tex></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
